The retrieved context does not contain operational patient or treatment records, so it cannot tell us which specific patients have received such treatments. It only provides schema and business-concept metadata.

From the schema, the relevant path to identify them would be: TREATMENTS.patient_id → PATIENTS.patient_id to get the patient, and TREATMENTS.provider_id → PROVIDERS.provider_id to get the provider who performed the treatment. To determine whether that provider is a cardiology department provider, use PROVIDERS.department_id → DEPARTMENTS.department_id and filter the department to Cardiology using DEPARTMENTS.department_name, since the glossary explicitly gives Cardiology as an example of a Department. The PATIENTS table represents the Patient Master Record and includes patient_id, mrn, first_name, last_name, and other demographic fields, so those would be the patient-identifying columns to return.

The context also shows a related distinction: TREATMENTS has its own department_id, described as the department where the treatment occurred, while PROVIDERS.department_id is the provider’s primary department affiliation. So if the question means “treated by providers whose primary department is Cardiology,” the join should go through PROVIDERS.department_id. If instead it means “treated in the Cardiology department,” then TREATMENTS.department_id → DEPARTMENTS.department_id is the relevant path.

Relevant columns present in the context are:
PATIENTS.patient_id, mrn, first_name, last_name;
TREATMENTS.patient_id, provider_id, department_id, treatment_name, cpt_code, treatment_date;
PROVIDERS.provider_id, first_name, last_name, specialty, department_id;
DEPARTMENTS.department_id, department_name, department_code, parent_department_id, service_line.

What remains unavailable is the actual list of patients, because no row-level data is included in the retrieved context.
